Power generation prediction¶

Author Yrieix Leprince
Date April 2018.
Context Work done in order to candidate at Craft AI (http://www.craft.ai/)
Datasets https://www.dropbox.com/s/pqenrr2mcvl0hk9/GEFCom2014.zip?dl=0
Goal Predict the power generation for 10 wind farms given wind zonal and meridional components (at 10 and 100 meters).

The following notebook is based on the GEFCom2014_Data/Wind/task01/Task1_W_Zone1_10/ dataset.

0. Load Data¶

The data used is located in the _Wind/task01/Task1_W_Zone110/ directory. It represents ten months of records for the ten wind farms (ie. ZONEID).

In [3]:
path = '../data/GEFCom2014_Data/Wind/task01/Task1_W_Zone1_10/'
In [4]:
# Load data
task01 = pd.read_csv(path + 'Task1_W_Zone1.csv')
for i in range(2, 11):
    task01 = task01.append(pd.read_csv(path + 'Task1_W_Zone{}.csv'.format(i)))

1. Data exploration¶

We have a column TIMESTAMP giving the record timestamp. We choose to set this column as index in order to work with timeseries.

In [5]:
# Set TIMESTAMP as index
task01.TIMESTAMP = pd.to_datetime(task01.TIMESTAMP) - pd.to_timedelta(1, unit='h')
task01.set_index(['TIMESTAMP'], drop=True, inplace=True)
task01.sort_index(ascending=True, inplace=True)

task01.head()

Now we have our dataframe indexed on timestamps. We have 24 records per day (every hour) for each of the 10 wind farms, from the 2012-01-01 to the 2012-09-30. Our dataframe contains the following columns:

Column Description
ZONEID  Wind farm id. 
TARGETVAR Wind farm power generation, normalized by its nominal capacity.
U10 Zonal wind component, measured at 10 meters above ground level.
V10 Meridional wind component, measured at 10 meters above ground level.
U100 Zonal wind component, measured at 100 meters above ground level.
V100 Meridional wind component, measured at 100 meters above ground level.

1.1. Trends analysis¶

Graphs below show the TARGETVAR trends over time.

In [6]:
trends = {
    'daily'     : 24      ,#ie. 24 hours/records a day
    'weekly'    : 24*7    ,#ie. 24 hours/records a day * 7  days
    'monthly'   : 24*30   ,#ie. 24h * 30 days
    'quarterly' : 24*30*3 ,#ie. 24h * 30d * 3 months
}
In [7]:
for trend in trends.keys():
    plt.title(trend.upper() + ' TREND', fontdict=FONT)
    plt.ylabel('Power generation', fontdict=FONT)
    for zID in np.unique(task01.ZONEID):
        plt.plot(task01[task01.ZONEID == zID].TARGETVAR.rolling(trends[trend]).mean(), 
                 label='Zone {}'.format(zID))
    plt.legend(loc=1, prop={'size': FONT['size']})
    plt.show()

Daily, weekly and monthly power generation trends are quite irregular and difficult to visualize.

On the quaterly trend one can clearly spot a trend shared by all wind farms. The power generation is low during summer and generally increases during the other seasons.

Both 10 and 100 meters records respect the same tendancy. Above is only presented the second graph.

One can see that the power generation is well correlated to U and V features. When (U,V) are small, the power generation is low, whereas a couple of (U,V) with high values (positive or not) leads to a high power generation.

2. Data enrichment¶

In order to help our algorithms let's compute two new features wind_10 and wind_100 that correspond to the norm of the vectors [U10,V10] and [U100, V100].

This data enrichment aims at representing the wind strength, whatever its direction.

In [9]:
compute_wind_stength = lambda row: pd.Series({'wind_10':norm([row.U10, row.V10]), 
                                              'wind_100':norm([row.U100, row.V100])})
In [10]:
task01 = task01.merge(task01.apply(compute_wind_stength, axis=1), left_index=True, right_index=True)

From the graph above one can see that the wind strength at 10 meters is also linearly correlated to the 100's. It means that the information contained in columns wind_X are quite redundant.

3. Regressors exploration¶

In this section we are trying to use different regressors to predict the power production from the features detailed above.

Here we are doing the following hypothesis: records are time independant .

It means that all weather measurements done in a wind farm are independants from each others.

In [13]:
features = ['ZONEID', 'U10', 'V10', 'U100', 'V100', 'wind_10', 'wind_100']

X = task01[features]
y = task01['TARGETVAR']

del task01

Scaling:

This step is essential for non tree-based algorithms.

In [14]:
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler

scaler = StandardScaler()
X_std = scaler.fit_transform(X, y)

del X

Train/test split:

As we do not have the POWER GENERATION values for the given test set, we generate below a new one from the given data. So we are able to train and evaluate by ourselves our algorithms.

In [15]:
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split

X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X_std, y, test_size=0.30, random_state=42)

3.1 Tree-based regressors¶

As trees are estimators that have an easy to catch internal logic, we will mainly focus on them in this subsection.

  • First we are testing single tree-based regressors:
    • Decision Tree
    • ExtraTree
In [16]:
from sklearn.model_selection import cross_val_score

def return_CV_scores(regressor, CV=10):
    scores = cross_val_score(regressor, X_train, y_train, cv=CV, n_jobs=-1)
    mean =  scores.mean()
    std = scores.std()
    print('Scores statistics:\n\tMean:', mean)
    print('\tStd:', std)
    return {'mean' : mean, 'std' : std}

Each algorithm performance is stored in the regressors dictionnary initialized below:

In [17]:
regressors={}

from sklearn.tree import DecisionTreeRegressor

3.2 Ensemble Regressors¶

In this subsection we are exploring ensemble learning methods, still based on tree regressors:

  • Random Forest
  • AdaBoost
  • Gradient Boosting
  • ExtraTrees

3.2.1 Random Forest Regressor¶

"A __random forest__ is a meta estimator that fits a number of classifying decision trees on various sub-samples of the dataset and use averaging to improve the predictive accuracy and control over-fitting. The sub-sample size is always the same as the original input sample size but the samples are drawn with replacement if bootstrap=True (default)." http://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/ensemble.html#forest

In [22]:
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestRegressor

RF_reg = RandomForestRegressor(random_state=42, n_jobs=-1)
In [23]:
%%time
regressors['RF_reg'] = return_CV_scores(RF_reg)

Scores statistics:
	Mean: 0.972037986957306
	Std: 0.000911276483045163
CPU times: user 1.11 s, sys: 150 ms, total: 1.26 s
Wall time: 2min 43s

3.2.2 AdaBoost Regressor¶

" An __AdaBoost regressor__ is a meta-estimator that begins by fitting a regressor on the original dataset and then fits additional copies of the regressor on the same dataset but where the weights of instances are adjusted according to the error of the current prediction. As such, subsequent regressors focus more on difficult cases. " http://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/ensemble.html#adaboost

In [24]:
from sklearn.ensemble import AdaBoostRegressor

AdaB_reg = AdaBoostRegressor(DT_reg, random_state=42)

" __Gradient Boosting__ builds an additive model in a forward stage-wise fashion; it allows for the optimization of arbitrary differentiable loss functions. In each stage a regression tree is fit on the negative gradient of the given loss function. " http://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/ensemble.html#gradient-boosting

3.3 Exploring other regressors¶

This third subsection aims at exploring other algorithms (non tree-based). It is usually a good practice to explore algorithms with very different internal mecanisms to see how they perform on the given data. If all the regressors would have been less performant, we could have done an ensemble learning method like bagging to combine the strengths of each of them.

We only test the following regressors:

  • K-nearest neighbors
  • Mutli-layer Perceptron (from sklearn)

3.3.1 K-nearest neighbors¶

"The target is predicted by local interpolation of the targets associated of the nearest neighbors in the training set." http://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/neighbors.html#regression

In [30]:

3.3.2 Multi-layer Perceptron regressor¶

Class __MLPRegressor__ implements a multi-layer perceptron (MLP) that trains using backpropagation with no activation function in the output layer, which can also be seen as using the identity function as activation function. Therefore, it uses the square error as the loss function, and the output is a set of continuous values. http://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/neural_networks_supervised.html#regression

In [32]:
from sklearn.neural_network import MLPRegressor

MLP_reg = MLPRegressor(hidden_layer_sizes=(20,),
                       activation='relu',

                       random_state=42)

4. Understanding predictions¶

After having tested several regressors, here is a quick view of the performances:

In [36]:
regressors_labels = [r for r in regressors.keys()]
regressors_means = [regressors[r]['mean'] for r in regressors.keys()]
regressors_stds = [regressors[r]['std'] for r in regressors.keys()]


fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(20,5))

idx = np.arange(len(regressors_labels))
plt.bar(idx, regressors_means, width=0.3, yerr=regressors_stds)
plt.xticks(idx, regressors_labels)

ax.set_frame_on(False)
plt.grid(True)

plt.show()

Each regressor has some strengths and weaknesses. At this point the client can choose which algorithm fits the best his needs. It can be the speed, the scalability, the robustness... The client can also choose a combinaison of regressors.

In this specific work we continue with the Decision Tree regressor, for the following reasons:

  • Decision Trees are estimators that have an internal logic easy to catch. The user can understand each prediction by following the tree architecture built during the training process.
  • Decision Trees can also explain features importance which can be very useful when the data is costly to produce: the user knows which feature really matters for the regressor.
  • The decision tree regressor DT_reg used above returned quite good results (score above 96%), for a modest processing cost (the cross validated training lasts less than 25s with 10 folds).

4.1 Focus on the Decision Tree¶

4.1.1 Features importance¶

Features importance is a step that allow the user to understand which features are mainly considerated for the regression. Scores given to each feature can vary a lot between regressors.

In [37]:
DT_reg.fit(X_train, y_train)

print('Features importance:')
for score, feature in sorted(zip(DT_reg.feature_importances_, features), reverse=True):
    print('\t',feature, "%.2f" % score, '%')

Features importance:
	 wind_100 0.27 %
	 V100 0.24 %
	 U100 0.24 %
	 ZONEID 0.10 %
	 U10 0.08 %
	 V10 0.06 %
	 wind_10 0.01 %

Lines above describe our Decision Tree features importance.

During its training process the Decision Tree splits samples on their features to order them within different divisions. The decision tree tries to minimize the inner entropy and to maximize the entropy between two branches of a split. The sooner the split in the tree architecture, the more important is the feature.

The wind strength at 100 meters is the feature that influences the most the power generation. Then come the wind components U and V at 100 meters.

4.1.2 Parameters Fine tuning¶

Let's show how to fine tune our model based on the example of the max_depth parameter.

In [38]:
maxdepth = 50

DT_error=[]
DT_processing_time = []

for depth in range(1, maxdepth):
    t0 = time()
    DT_reg = DecisionTreeRegressor(max_depth=depth, random_state=42)
    DT_reg.fit(X_train, y_train)
    DT_error.append(1-DT_reg.score(X_test, y_test))
    DT_processing_time.append(time()-t0)
In [42]:
fig, ax1 = plt.subplots()
plt.title('Compromise between performance and computational cost',
          fontdict=FONT)

ax1.plot(range(1, maxdepth), DT_error, 'b-')
ax1.set_xlabel('Max_Depth', fontdict=FONT)


ax1.set_ylabel('Error rate (%)', color='b', fontdict=FONT)
ax1.tick_params('y', colors='b')

ax2 = ax1.twinx()
ax2.plot(range(1, maxdepth), DT_processing_time, 'r')
ax2.set_ylabel('Computational cost (time)', color='r', fontdict=FONT)
ax2.tick_params('y', colors='r')

fig.tight_layout()

plt.show()

The graph above illustrates the compromise between the computational time and the error rate. Here we are only considering a single decision tree hyper-parameter: the max_depth. Algorithms can have five or ten hyper-parameters. This fine-tuning step in a machine learning project aims at choosing the best parameters combinaison to fit project needs.

In order to fine-tune the algorithm hyper-parameters without overfitting on the test set, we should have used a validation set. But in this specific work we will stay pragmatic and keep default parameters as they perform very well on the data. On a more complex project a grid-search could have been necessary to explore more combinaisons of the algorithm hyper-parameters.

5. Conclusion and Prediction simulation¶

Conclusion:

  • The goal of this work was to predict the power generation for each of the ten wind farms, given the weather forecast (ie. the wind zonal and meridional components at 10 and 100 meters).

  • We tried different regressors to finally choose a simple Decision Tree regressor as it performed very well on the data.

Prediction:

  • The last step is to simulate a real power production prediction on the test set (ie. on data that the algorithm has never seen during the training process):
In [40]:
power_generation_prediction = DT_reg.predict(X_test)  # stores predicted values
In [41]:
print('Prediction score with the Decision Tree regressor %.2f' % DT_reg.score(X_test, y_test) + '%')

Prediction score with the Decision Tree regressor 0.97%

As expected, the decision tree regressor DT_reg performed well on new data.
